# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The **1933 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the first edition of the All-Star Game known as the "Midsummer Classic".
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] This was the first official playing of the midseason exhibition baseball game between Major League Baseball's (MLB's) National League (NL) and American League (AL) All-Star teams.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game was held on July 6, 1933, at Comiskey Park in Chicago, Illinois, the home of the AL's Chicago White Sox.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game resulted in the AL defeating the NL, 4–2, in two hours and five minutes.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The first official All-Star Game came 22 years after the Addie Joss Benefit Game of July 24, 1911, when the American League's Cleveland Naps faced a team of all-stars from other American League teams at League Park in Cleveland, Ohio; the game was won by the all-star squad, 5–3.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The first official MLB All-Star exhibition game on July 6, 1933, was held at Comiskey Park (1910–1990) and was part of the 1933 Chicago World's Fair during the city's centennial.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The 1933 MLB All-Star Game was the idea of Arch Ward, the sports editor of the *Chicago Tribune*, after the Mayor of Chicago, Edward J.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Kelly, had first approached the *Tribune's* publisher for a major sport event.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game was intended to be a one-time event to boost morale during the Great Depression.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Ward decided that the fans would select the starting nine players and the managers the other nine players for each of the NL and AL All-Star teams.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The *Tribune* called it the "Game of the Century", and 55 newspapers across the country printed the fans' ballots in their papers.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The *Tribune* estimated the game's attendance on July 6, 1933, at 49,000.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The proceeds ($45,000, net gate receipts) from the game went to a charity for disabled and needy major league players.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The All-Star Game would afterwards be known as MLB's "Midsummer Classic".
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The legendary Babe Ruth of the Yankees highlighted the game by hitting a two-run home run to right field in the bottom of the third inning and catching a fly ball up against the scoreboard in right-center field in the top of the eighth inning.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Ruth was greeted at home plate by the AL/Chicago White Sox batboy John McBride and teammate Lou Gehrig.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Twenty of the game's thirty-six All-Stars including Ruth would later be inducted into the National Baseball Hall of Fame at Cooperstown, New York.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Both the game's managers, five out of six coaches, and two out of the four umpires on the field that day would also be future Hall of Famers.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Two AL All-Stars were White Sox players, starting third baseman Jimmy Dykes and starting center fielder Al Simmons.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Yankee Lefty Gomez was the winning pitcher for the American League.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The NL team wore specially made gray uniforms and navy blue caps with "National League" in navy blue felt letters on the front of the jersey, a large navy blue felt number on the back and "NL" in white letters printed on the navy caps.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The AL team members each wore their home uniform.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The NL members were allowed to keep their All-Star uniforms and caps.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In 1934, each NL member used their home uniform and cap.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game's official AL baseball was changed to an official NL baseball and the AL home plate umpire was replaced by a NL home plate umpire after the top of the 5th inning.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] 60 baseballs autographed by All-Star players were given out before the game started.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Personnel in *italics* have since been inducted into the National Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The umpires rotated positions clockwise in the middle of the fifth inning, with Klem moving behind the plate.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Chick Hafey of the National League had the first hit, a bloop single to center field to lead off the second inning.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The American League got on the board first in the bottom of the second.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] NL pitcher Bill Hallahan issued one-out walks to Jimmy Dykes and Joe Cronin.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Two batters later, the game's winning pitcher Lefty Gomez, singled home Dykes for the AL's first run.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In the bottom of the third, after a walk to Charlie Gehringer, Babe Ruth famously hit the first home run in All-Star Game history, putting the AL up 3–0.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Hallahan was chased from the game after walking Lou Gehrig immediately afterward, and was replaced by Lon Warneke.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] General Crowder replaced Gomez to start the fourth inning.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In the sixth, Warneke hit a one-out triple and scored on a Pepper Martin groundout.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Frankie Frisch followed with a home run to bring the NL to within a run, but after a Chuck Klein single, Crowder would escape the inning without giving up any more damage.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Cronin led off the bottom of the sixth with a single.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] After advancing on a bunt, he scored on an Earl Averill single to extend the lead to 4–2.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Crowder would be replaced by Lefty Grove in the top of the seventh, while Warneke was replaced by Carl Hubbell in the bottom of the inning.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The NL looked to have a chance in the top of the eighth.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] With Frisch on first with two outs, Hafey lined a shot to right field that looked like it could be a home run, but Ruth reached over the wall to catch it, denying the NL a chance to tie the game.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Grove retired the side in order in the ninth to secure the American League's victory.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The **1934 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the second edition of the mid-summer classic between the all-stars of the American League (AL) and National League (NL), the two leagues comprising Major League Baseball.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] It was held on July 10 in Manhattan, New York City, at the Polo Grounds, the home of the New York Giants of the National League, the defending World Series champions.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The American League won 9–7, and every starter on both teams except Wally Berger was later inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game is well known among baseball historians for the performance of NL starting pitcher Carl Hubbell of the host Giants.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] After allowing the first two batters to reach base on a single and a base on balls, Hubbell struck out five of the game's best hitters – Babe Ruth, Lou Gehrig, Jimmie Foxx, Al Simmons, and Joe Cronin – in succession, setting a longstanding All-Star Game record for consecutive strikeouts.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Trailing 4–2, the American League scored six times in the top of the fifth inning to take the lead for good.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The teams combined for sixteen runs on 22 hits; the two home runs were hit early in the game by the NL (Frankie Frisch, Joe Medwick), both with the St.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Louis Cardinals, the World Series champions later that year.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Players in *italics* have since been inducted into the National Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Cy Pfirman, NL (home), Brick Owens, AL (first base), Dolly Stark, NL (second base), George Moriarty, AL (third base); the umpires rotated positions clockwise in the middle of the fifth inning, with Owens moving behind the plate.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The **1935 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the third playing of the mid-summer classic between the all-stars of the American League (AL) and National League (NL), the two leagues comprising Major League Baseball.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game was held on July 8, 1935, at Cleveland Stadium in Cleveland, Ohio, hosted by the Cleveland Indians of the American League.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game resulted in the American League defeating the National League 4–1.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The umpires rotated positions clockwise in the middle of the fifth inning, with Magerkurth moving behind the plate.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Lefty Gomez of the Yankees pitches six innings, gives up three hits and is the winning pitcher.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Jimmie Foxx drives in three with a two-run homer and a single.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] The **1935 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1935 season.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] The 32nd edition of the World Series, it matched the Detroit Tigers and the Chicago Cubs.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] The Tigers won in six games for their first championship in five Series appearances, as they had lost in 1907, 1908, 1909, and 1934.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] This was the first championship ever won by a Detroit-based team.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] The Tigers won despite losing the services of first baseman Hank Greenberg.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] In Game 2, Greenberg collided with Cubs catcher Gabby Hartnett and broke his wrist, sidelining him for the rest of the Series.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] The Cubs had won 21 consecutive games in September (still a record as of 2021), eventually taking the National League pennant by four games over the defending World Series champions, the St.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] In Game 6, Tommy Bridges pitched a complete-game victory to win the Series for Detroit.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] With the score tied 3–3 in the top of the ninth inning, Bridges gave up a leadoff triple to Stan Hack, but retired the next three batters without the runner on third scoring.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] In the bottom of the ninth, Goose Goslin drove in the winning run with two outs.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] After the game, manager Mickey Cochrane said the following of Bridges' gutsy performance: "A hundred and fifty pounds of courage.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] In addition to Bridges, the Tigers had a hitting hero.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] Right fielder Pete Fox accumulated ten hits and an average of .385 for the Series.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] Detroit owner Frank Navin, then 64 years old, had been running the organization for 30 years and had seen four of his teams win American League pennants, only to lose four World Series.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] Six weeks after the Tigers finally won the World Series in October 1935, Navin suffered a heart attack while riding a horse and died.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] A pitching duel between Lon Warneke and Schoolboy Rowe, both of whom went the distance, was decided by its leadoff batter, Augie Galan, doubling, and scoring on an error by Rowe that allowed Billy Herman to reach and eventually score on a Gabby Hartnett single.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] Frank Demaree added a homer in the ninth inning for the visiting Cubs.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] In the bottom of the first, Jo-Jo White hit a leadoff single and scored on a double by Mickey Cochrane, who scored on Charlie Gehringer's single before Hank Greenberg's two-run home run knocked Cubs' starter Charlie Root out of the game.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] In the fourth, Roy Henshaw got two outs before letting the Tigers load the bases on a single, hit-by-pitch and walk.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] A wild pitch scored a run, then after a walk reloaded the bases, Gehringer's two-run single made it 7–0 Tigers.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] The Cubs got on the board in the fifth when Phil Cavarretta reached first on an error, moved to second on a groundout and scored on Billy Jurges's single.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] The Cubs got two more runs in the seventh on Billy Herman's single with runners on second and third, but the Tigers added a run in the bottom half on Pete Fox's RBI single off Fabian Kowalik.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] Tommy Bridges pitched a complete game as the Tigers' 8–3 tied the series heading to Chicago.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] In Game 3, Frank Demaree's leadoff home run in the second off Elden Auker put Chicago on the board.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] A one-out single and subsequent error put runners on first and third before Bill Lee's ground out made it 2–0 Cubs.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] They added a run in the fifth when Billy Jurges drew a leadoff walk, moved to second on a sacrifice bunt and scored on Augie Galan's single.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] The Tigers got on the board in the sixth when Goose Goslin singled off Lee and scored on Pete Fox's triple.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] In the eighth, after a walk and double, Goslin's two-run single tied the game and knocked Lee out.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] Reliever Lon Warneke allowed two singles, the second of which to Billy Rogell scoring a run, then Fox stole home to make it 5–3 Tigers.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] Detroit brought back Game 1 starter Schoolboy Rowe in relief.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] He allowed three straight one-out singles in the ninth, the last of which to Ken O'Dea, before Augie Galan's sacrifice fly sent the game into extra innings, but Rowe nailed down the victory after Jo-Jo White's RBI single scored the winning run off Larry French in the 11th.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] This game remarkably featured four ejections.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] The Tigers lost coach Del Baker while The Cubs lost Woody English, Tuck Stainback and manager Charlie Grimm.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] Neither English nor Stainback were in the game.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] Chicago threatened against Crowder with a pair of one-out hits in the ninth, but Stan Hack grounded into a game-ending 6-4-3 double play.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] Staving off elimination, the Cubs got a two-run home run from Chuck Klein after a leadoff triple in the second.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] They added another run in the seventh on Billy Herman's RBI double off Schoolboy Rowe.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] They replaced Lon Warneke after six innings with right-hander Bill Lee, who gave up Detroit's only run in the ninth on three consecutive singles (the last of which to Pete Fox before settling down to retire the final three batters.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] This was the first of three World Series games that the Cubs have won in Wrigley Field (where they had previously lost 6 Series games).
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] The other wins were Game 6 in 1945, and Game 5 in 2016.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] In Game 6, Pete Fox's RBI double off Larry French put the Tigers on the board.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] Billy Herman's RBI single tied the game in the third off Tommy Bridges, who put the Tigers back in front in the fourth with an RBI groundout with two on, but Herman's two-run home run in the fifth put the Cubs ahead 3–2.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] The Tigers tied the game in the sixth when Billy Rogell doubled with two outs and scored on Marv Owen's single.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] Stan Hack tripled to lead off the top of the ninth for the Cubs, but was left stranded at third.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] In the bottom of the ninth, Mickey Cochrane singled and moved to second on a groundout before Goose Goslin's walk-off single won it in front of Detroit's home fans, pitcher Tommy Bridges getting his second win of the Series.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] When the Detroit Tigers won the 1935 World Series, the city of Detroit was mired in the Great Depression, which had hit the city and its industries particularly hard.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] With the Stanley Cup win, the city had seen three major league championships in less than a year.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] The Tigers would return to the World Series in 1940 World Series, but they would narrowly fall to the Cincinnati Reds in seven games after being nine outs away from the championship in Game 7, which would be the last time the Tigers lost in the World Series until 2006.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] The Tigers would win their next title in 1945 in a rematch against the Cubs in seven games.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1935-world-series] The Cubs returned to the World Series in 1938, but were swept by the New York Yankees, becoming the third victim of a Yankees four-peat from 1936 to 1939.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The **1936 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the fourth playing of the mid-summer classic between the all-stars of the American League (AL) and National League (NL), the two leagues comprising Major League Baseball.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game was held on July 7, 1936, at National League Park in Boston, Massachusetts, the home of the Boston Bees of the National League.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game resulted in the National League defeating the American League 4–3.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] It was the National League's first win in All-Star Game history.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Joe DiMaggio became the first rookie player in MLB history to start in an All-Star Game.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The umpires rotated positions clockwise in the middle of the fifth inning, with Summers moving behind the plate.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Joe DiMaggio became the first rookie to play in an All-Star Game; he was hitless in five-at-bats and made an error in right field.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] The **1936 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1936 season.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] The 33rd edition of the World Series, it matched the New York Yankees against the New York Giants, with the Yankees winning in six games to earn their fifth championship.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] The Yankees played their first World Series without Babe Ruth and their first with Joe DiMaggio, Ruth having been released by the Yankees after the 1934 season.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] He retired in 1935 as a member of the Boston Braves.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] Carl Hubbell won Game 1, allowing only one run on George Selkirk's home run and seven hits.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] After Dick Bartell's fifth inning home run off Red Ruffing tied the game, an RBI single by Gus Mancuso scoring Mel Ott, who doubled to lead off, in the sixth inning put the Giants up 2–1.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] They padded their lead in the eighth inning.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] Two singles and a walk loaded the bases before a walk to Burgess Whitehead and sacrifice fly by Travis Jackson scored a run each.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] Hubbell's two-run single capped the game's scoring.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] He pitched a perfect ninth as the Giants took a 1–0 series lead.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] The Yankees won Game 2 at the Polo Grounds by an 18–4 count, setting Series records (as of 2023) for the biggest margin of victory in a World Series game (14 runs) and the most runs scored in one game with 18.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] They loaded the bases with no outs in the first off Hal Schumacher on two singles and a walk before sacrifice flies by Lou Gehrig and Bill Dickey put them up 2–0.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] Two walks and a wild pitch by Lefty Gomez in the second inning allowed the Giants to cut the lead to 2–1, but the Yankees blew the game open in the third inning.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] A single, walk and error loaded the bases with no outs.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] Al Smith relieved Schumacher and allowed a two-run single to Gehrig and RBI single to Dickey.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] A one-out walk reloaded the bases before Tony Lazzeri's grand slam off Dick Coffman made it 9–1 Yankees.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] The Giants scored their last three runs in the fourth inning on a bases loaded walk to Dick Bartell followed by a two-run single by Bill Terry.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] The Yankees added a run in the sixth on Joe DiMaggio's sacrifice fly with two on off Frank Gabler, then loaded the bases in the seventh on a walk and two singles before Lazzeri's flyout and Gomez's groundout scored a run each.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] In the ninth, Jake Powell drew a leadoff walk off Harry Gumbert, stole second, moved to third on a groundout, and scored on Gomez's single.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] After another single, back-to-back RBI singles by Red Rolfe and DiMaggio made it 15–4 Yankees.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] One out later, Dickey's three-run home run capped the scoring.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] DiMaggio made a tremendous play in Game 2.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] With two outs in the bottom of the ninth inning, Hank Leiber drove the ball 490 feet (150 m) deep into dead center, and Joe caught the ball running up the steps of the clubhouse.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] This remarkable catch was at least 40 feet (12 m) further than Willie Mays' far more celebrated catch of Vic Wertz's drive to deep straightaway center in Game 1 of the 1954 World Series.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] After DiMaggio's game-ending grab, President Roosevelt, who was in attendance, saluted Joe for his great catch as he rode off in the presidential limousine.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] All three ninth-inning outs were made by DiMaggio.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] Yankee second baseman Tony Lazzeri became only the second player ever to hit a grand slam home run in the World Series.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] Elmer Smith of the Cleveland Indians had been the sole achiever of that feat in World Series play, doing so in Game 5 of the 1920 World Series.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] After seeing the score of this game, legendary Dodgers broadcaster Vin Scully (then 9 years old) became a Giants fan as he felt bad for the losing side.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] He credited this game as the game that made him fall in love with the game of baseball.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] Pat Malone pitched a scoreless ninth for the save.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] The Yankees struck first in the second when Jake Powell reached on an error and scored on George Selkirk's single off Carl Hubbell.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] Next inning, Frank Crosetti hit a leadoff double and scored on Red Rolfe's single, then Lou Gehrig's two-run home run gave the Yankees a 4–0 lead.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] Jimmy Ripple's RBI single in the fourth off Monte Pearson put the Giants on the board.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] Bill Terry's groundout with runners on first and third in the eighth cut the Yankees' lead to two, but they got that run back in the bottom half when Gehrig hit a leadoff double off Frank Gabler and scored on Powell's single.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] Pearson won his first World Series game (he won three more, in 1937, 1938, and 1939).
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] The Giants struck first with back-to-back leadoff doubles by Jo-Jo Moore and Dick Bartell off Red Ruffing.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] RBI singles by Jimmy Ripple and Burgess Whitehead made it 3–0 Giants.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] George Selkirk's home run off Hal Schumacher in the second put the Yankees on the board.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] Next inning, with runners on second and third, an error on Frank Crosetti's groundball allowed another run to score.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] A similar situation in the sixth on Burgess Whitehead's groundball allowed the Giants to pad their lead to 4–2, but in the bottom half, three consecutive two-out singles allowed the Yankees to tie the game.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] Bill Terry's sacrifice fly in the top of the tenth inning off Pat Malone, scoring Jo-Jo Moore, who doubled to leadoff and moved to third on a sacrifice bunt, helped the Giants win Game 5, 5–4, to extend the series to a Game Six.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] The Giants loaded the bases in the first off Lefty Gomez on a single and two walks before Mel Ott drove in two with a double, but Jake Powell's home-run after a two-out triple off Freddie Fitzsimmons tied the game in the second.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] Next inning, Lou Gehrig's sacrifice fly after two one-out singles put the Yankees up 3–2.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] They extended their lead to 5–2 in the fourth on four singles, two of which (by Gomez and Red Rolfe) scored a run each.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] Ott's home run in the fifth cut the lead to 5–3, then in the seventh, Dick Bartell hit a leadoff double and scored on Bill Terry's single to make it a one-run game.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] Tony Lazzeri's RBI single in the eighth off Slick Castleman made it 6–4 Yankees, but the Giants again cut the lead to one on Jo-Jo Moore's home run in the bottom half off Johnny Murphy.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] The Yankees, though, blew it open in the ninth.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] After two leadoff singles off Dick Coffman, an error on Bill Dickey's fielder's choice allowed one run to score.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] A walk loaded the bases before Powell drove in two more runs for the Yankees with a single.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] Harry Gumbert relieved Coffman and after a walk loaded the bases, Murphy's single, Crosetti's walk, Rolfe's groundout, and Joe DiMaggio's single scored a run each to make it 13–5 Yankees.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] It was the first time in history that a team would score seven runs in the 9th inning of a postseason game.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] No team has surpassed this mark, although five have tied it (the next one to occur after this one took place 34 years later).
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] Murphy retired the Giants in order in the bottom of the ninth to give the Yankees the championship.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] The Yankees' fifth championship tied the record at that time, which was shared by the Boston Red Sox and the Philadelphia Athletics, who also had five World Series titles.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] The Yankees also tied the American League record at that time for the most World Series appearances with eight, also shared with the Athletics.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] They broke both records the following year.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] The Giants appeared in their 11th World Series, extending the record they already held at that time, and their seventh World Series defeat also extended the record they already owned.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] DiMaggio would go on to be the only person to play on four World Championship teams in his first four years in the big leagues, the 1936–39 Yankees.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] The Yankee left fielder Jake Powell started the year with the Washington Senators before coming over in the middle of the year in a trade for Ben Chapman.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] In this Series, the unheralded Powell would lead all hitters in hits (10), batting average (.455), runs (8) and walks (4), add a home run with five runs batted in, and grab the Yankees' only stolen base.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] However, it proved to be a fleeting moment of fame for the troubled ballplayer, who gambled away the World Series check not long after before fizzling out with the Yankees by 1940, amidst controversial remarks involving him beating people as a cop to train in the offseason.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1936-world-series] He died in 1948 at the age of 40 after shooting himself in a police station for passing bad checks.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1937-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The **1937 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the fifth playing of the midsummer classic between the All-Stars of the American League (AL) and National League (NL), the two leagues comprising Major League Baseball.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1937-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game was held on July 7, 1937, at Griffith Stadium in Washington, D.C., the home of the Washington Senators of the American League.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1937-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The American League defeated the National League, 8 to 3.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1937-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game, attended by President Franklin D.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1937-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Roosevelt, is remembered because of a play in which Earl Averill of the Indians hit a ball that struck Cardinals pitcher Dizzy Dean on the toe, breaking it; complications from this injury shortened the career of the future Hall of Fame pitcher.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1937-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The umpires changed assignments in the middle of the fifth inning – McGowan and Barr swapped positions, also Pinelli and Quinn swapped positions.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The **1948 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the 15th playing of the midsummer classic between the all-stars of the American League (AL) and National League (NL), the two leagues comprising Major League Baseball.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game was held on July 13, 1948, at Sportsman's Park in St.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Louis, Missouri, the home of both the St.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Louis Browns of the American League (who were the designated host team) and the St.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game resulted in the American League defeating the National League 5–2.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] This was the first All-Star Game to be broadcast on television, albeit only locally.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Richie Ashburn became only the third rookie player in MLB history to start in an All-Star Game after Joe DiMaggio, (1939) and Dick Wakefield, (1943).
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The lone representative of the host team was Al Zarilla, a reserve outfielder for the AL, who entered the game playing right field in the top of the 5th inning, and was hitless in two at bats.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The umpires changed assignments in the middle of the fifth inning – Berry and Reardon swapped positions, also Stewart and Paparella swapped positions.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The NL scored two runs in the top of the 1st inning, on a leadoff single by rookie Richie Ashburn, and later a two-run home run by Stan Musial with one out.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] It would be the only runs the NL would score.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The AL got one run back in the bottom of the 2nd inning, on a home run by Hoot Evers.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] They later tied the score at 2–2 in the bottom of the 3rd, after two walks, a steal of third base by Mickey Vernon, and a sacrifice fly from Lou Boudreau.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In the bottom of the 4th, the AL pulled ahead with 3 runs; after loading the bases with two singles and a walk, Vic Raschi drove in two runs with a single, followed by one more run scoring on a lineout by Joe DiMaggio.
[src:1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] With the AL up 5–2, there would be no more scoring, despite the NL loading the bases in the 6th inning.
